<div class="text-wrap">
  <h4>The research process</h4>
  <p>
    A fellow designer and I conducted one-on-one interviews with 60 customers,
    a mix of self-service and business tiers. We hoped to learn the first
    thought that lead customers to decide our product was a something useful to
    them.
  </p>
  <p>
    We wanted to understand the context of our customers and the challenges they
    face in finding and using our product through the framework of
    <a href="http://www.elezea.com/2013/11/progress-making-forces/">forces</a>:
  </p>
  <ul class="bulleted-list">
    <li><p>The situations that pushed them to needing/wanting something like Segment.</p></li>
    <li><p>What drew customers to Segment.</p></li>
    <li><p>Habits that make it difficult to change to a new product or way of doing things.</p></li>
    <li><p>Anxieties that cause them to have a bad experience or hesitations with the product.</p></li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="work-image"><img src="/images/portfolio/segment-positioning/push-pull.png"></div>

<div class="text-wrap">
  <p>
    Understanding each of these quadrants for our customers helps us know exactly
    the job they are trying to do and how we might create solutions for them that
    they <em>actually</em> want.
  </p>
  <h4>How different jobs relate to each other</h4>
  <p>
    Jobs can have huge variety in granularity. Many smaller jobs collectively
    do a bigger job. For example, if you have a job of decorating your house,
    there are smaller jobs-to-be-done of hanging pictures, buying furniture,
    knocking down walls, etc.
  </p>
  <p>
    You can think of jobs as being nested, in a tree-like structure. Imagine
    each node representing a “job”. This is just an easy way to illustrate
    hierarchy and parent-child relationships. This keeps product planning
    focused on what the product is and is not, what should be built and what
    should not.
  </p>
  <p>
    If we use a tree to diagram the job of “chat” for Slack, you can see that
    Facebook, and Dropbox have a similar child job of chat or conversation, but if
    you follow that child to its parent, the purpose of each of those products are
    all very different.
  </p>
