<div class="text-wrap">
  <h6>1 - Stays at Gateway job</h6>
  <p>
    These  customers come in to Segment through the gateway job but don’t seem to
    expand their use of Segment beyond connecting analytics tools. Their concern is
    mainly with ease of implementation.
  </p>
  <h6>2 - Gateway job to Parent job</h6>
  <p>
    A larger amount of customers start at the gateway job, discover other jobs they
    can accomplish with the product, and come to think about us differently than
    when they initially came in. They come to realize the product as the product
    they <em>actually</em> wanted, and not the product they thought they wanted.
  </p>
  <h6>3 - Straight to Parent job</h6>
  <p>
    Customers more familiar with data and analytics tend to view our product
    through the lens of the Segment job, rather than *only *the gateway job.
    They’re thinking about the future of their data infrastructure and want to make
    sure the choices they make now will scale with them in the future.
  </p>
  <h4>Jobs to guide decision making</h4>
  <p>
    With our jobs defined, the team has a better idea of the value propositions
    that appeal to our customers and when those value propositions become
    relevant to them. It's now easier to orchestrate efforts across our whole
    team to strategically grow the customer base and help those customers get
    the most value out of Segment.
  </p>
</div>
